  <section class="margin-top-80 margin-bottom-80 max-width-720 mb-margin-top-60 mb-margin-bottom-60">
    <h2 class="font-size-28 mb-font-size-24 margin-bottom-20">What Factors Influence E-Bike Weight?</h2>
    <p class="margin-bottom-20">
      <span>
        The weight of an e-bike depends on various parts. Understanding these factors helps you balance performance and
        convenience.
      </span>
    </p>
    <h3 class="font-size-20 mb-font-size-16 margin-bottom-20 margin-top-48">1. Battery Size and Capacity</h3>
    <p class="margin-bottom-20">
      <span>
        The battery tends to add the most weight. Larger batteries, such as 48V units, weigh 10-20 lbs and offer more
        range but increase the bike’s weight. Using smaller batteries makes the bike lighter but shortens the travel
        distance before needing a recharge.
      </span>
    </p>
    <h3 class="font-size-20 mb-font-size-16 margin-bottom-20 margin-top-48">2. Motor Type and Placement</h3>
    <p class="margin-bottom-20">
      <span>
        Motor type and placement affect both weight and handling. Mid-drive motors sit at the bike's center, helping
        with weight distribution, which improves stability and makes climbing hills easier. Hub motors, placed on the
        wheels, are lighter but influence steering and stability differently. Dual-motor bikes provide greater power.
      </span>
    </p>
    <h3 class="font-size-20 mb-font-size-16 margin-bottom-20 margin-top-48">3. Frame Material</h3>
    <p class="margin-bottom-20">
      <span>
        The frame’s material plays a major role in determining the bike’s overall weight. Aluminum frames are affordable
        and durable but heavier. Frames made from carbon fiber weigh less and offer better handling. Steel frames offer
        the most durability but are the heaviest, making them suitable for rugged use.
      </span>
    </p>
    <h3 class="font-size-20 mb-font-size-16 margin-bottom-20 margin-top-48">4. Wheels and Tires</h3>
    <p class="margin-bottom-20">
      <span>
        Wider wheels and fat tires provide better traction and stability but add more weight. Slimmer tires are lighter
        and more efficient on paved roads but less effective on rough terrain. Selecting the right tires ensures a
        balance between stability and portability.
      </span>
    </p>
    <h3 class="font-size-20 mb-font-size-16 margin-bottom-20 margin-top-48">5. Suspension Systems and Accessories</h3>
    <p class="margin-bottom-20">
      <span>
        Full suspension improves comfort on bumpy roads but adds 4.4-11 lbs. Additional accessories, such as LCD
        screens, racks, and lights, also increase weight. Riders seeking both comfort and functionality might typically
        expect a heavier bike.
      </span>
      <br>
      <br>
      <span>
        However, Urtopia’s e-bikes manage to balance these two aspects by using lightweight yet durable carbon fiber
        frames. This material provides the strength needed for stability and comfort on longer rides, without adding
        unnecessary weight. As a result, Urtopia e-bikes offer a smooth, comfortable ride combined with easy handling
        and portability.
      </span>
    </p>
    <h3 class="font-size-20 mb-font-size-16 margin-bottom-20 margin-top-48">6. Pedal-Assist and Throttle Systems</h3>
    <p class="margin-bottom-20">
      <span>
        E-bikes with both pedal-assist and throttle need extra motor components, which adds to their overall weight.
        However, these features reduce fatigue by letting riders switch between assisted pedaling and throttle control,
        enhancing convenience during long rides.
      </span>
      <br>
      <br>
      <span>
        With a clear understanding of what influences e-bike weight, let’s explore the average weight of various types
        of e-bikes and their specific use cases.
      </span>
    </p>
